    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Last Thing Russia Needs: The S.U.V.</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Daniel F Becker of Sierra Club on General Motors' entry into Russian car market; says last thing Russians need are gas-guzzling sports utility vehicles (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''G.M. Takes a Leap of Faith Into the Russian Car Market'' (Business Day, Sept. 21):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''G.M. Takes a Leap of Faith Into the Russian Car Market'' (Business Day, Sept. 21):</p>
        <p>The last thing Russia needs right now is gas-guzzling S.U.V.'s that cost consumers at the gas pump, increase pollution and further destabilize the global political situation by driving up the price of oil.</p>
        <p>If General Motors wants to invest resources, why not invest in American know-how and existing technology that can make cars and S.U.V.'s that go farther on a gallon of gas? That would help the company compete with fast-moving foreign competitors like Toyota and Honda.</p>
        <p>Now that's an investment that both Russian and American consumers might be interested in.</p>
        <p>DANIEL F. BECKER  Washington, Sept. 23, 2002</p>
        <p>The writer is director, global warming and energy program, Sierra Club.</p>
      </block>
